Nov 17 2009 	"The worst hotel I have ever stayed at." - World Traveler	The reviewers who rated this place higher than two stars did so because of the hotel's location. Let's not give credit to a hotel for the development of its surrounding community. This hotel is bad and is not a value at the price of about $70 a night (+ $22 per day parking).As soon as I opened my room's door the smell of dirty old man body order pierced through my nose making my eyes water. On the floor was an open box of trojan condoms, an open bag of chips, and a pretzel. This place is not clean. The walls are super thin, so you can hear large trucks pass by the building and workers yelling outside early in the morning. A patron uptairs kept walking around all night and I could hear every amplified step. They have these old radiators that crack and hiss all night even if they are turned off. Forget about sleeping at this place. Oh and their linens are dirty and torn. Don't be lured in by their nice photos either, they must have used a wide angle lens to give the impression of space; these rooms are tiny. Their showers are as tiny as coffins so don't drop the soap because you'll twist like a contortionist to recover it.I've stayed in cheap hotels all over the world including in tijuana and I can say that any hotel in tijuana will beat this hell hole of a hotel; the location does not make up for this horrendous hotel experience.	
Nov 16 2009 	ideal location for reasonable price	My husband and I stayed at the Grant Plaza Hotel for the first time. Our usual hotel was booked up and we basically just wanted to find another hotel with the same attributes: clean room, central downtown SF location, and low price. We found all that in Grant Plaza. Be forewarned-- you won't get a chocolate on your pillow, the staff are helpful but not 5-star service, the rooms are small, the only toiletry provided is a round bar of soap, the linens &amp; mattress are thin, and our TV had 5 channels (one or which appeared to be live feed from a rooftop security camera).However, you trade all that for a value-priced room (we payed $80 for a double-sized bed) that is one block inside the chinatown gate, one block from union square, and a few blocks from North Beach. My husband and I walked all over, including the 1.5 miles from our hotel to Fisherman's Wharf/Pier 39. It was clean and reasonably quiet for being in the center of downtown. We used to live in the Bay Area plus visit frequently because of family and the fact that SF is our favorite city in the US. Take it from us, Grant Plaza Hotel provides a cheap night's sleep for those who want to explore what the city has to offer.	
