Apr 16 2007 	The best budget Hotel in the best city in the world.......(honestly!)	I cannot understand why the Grant Plaza gets the mauling it does in online reviews. It baffles me! I have stayed here on numerous occasions and have never at any time had a problem! The hotel is extremely well situated (being just inside Chinatown) and the ideal base for exploring the city on foot which I love to do. It is within a minute of the nearest convenience store, Starbucks coffee bar, and many restaurants of all kinds. It is also a central point enabling easy access to ALL of the sights that there are to see - most of which you can reach on foot. The walk through Chinatown into North Beach never ceases to fascinate me. I love it. The lobby is welcoming and the staff cannot do enough to help. Back to the Hotel - the rooms themselves are clean and bright and are cleaned daily by the maid. I have never had any experience of dirty bed linen or towels, and toiletries are supplied. OK, there is no air conditioning - big deal! I can only say that for the money offered, the rooms are clean and contain all the facilities needed (TV, Bed, Phone, Writing desk with complementary pen and pad, closet, shower cubicle, towels, soaps, shower gel, toilet paper and hairdryer (did I miss anything??). Oh yes, and there is broadband internet access in the lobby along with a wealth of city information literature and a soft drinks vending machine.What more do you need? Stay here - you will not regret it!	
Apr 13 2007 	Basic Clean Great Location and CHEAP	Basic, clean, doable. Great location as their promotional blurb says, in start of China town, close walk to Union Square, easy to get about on transport etc...They are also slowly updating the decor, which is needed.Now the beds were old, the furniture also old and a little worn, and the rooms not that big, but everything worked, it was clean and comfortable (if you're not spending the whole day in your suite!) and it was damn cheap! I agree with the recommendations from other reviews that you try to get a street facing higher level room (levels 4-5), and if you're a light sleeper bring ear plugs;) If your a couple backpacking, save some money and get better private accommodation here IMO. If you're a tourist, keen to be out and about, then this is perfectly suited as long as you don't need plush surroundings while you sleep;) Oh, and you'll need to go out for your morning coffee...	
Feb 23 2007	Spent 9 Nights	Stayed Feb. 10, 2007 through Feb. 19, 2007 on the 5th floor. Booked via http://cheaprooms.com/. Great location - 1 block inside of Chinatown and within walking distance (2 to 3 miles) of most everything worth seeing. I paid $64 a night when the average for a SF hotel room is $170. Downside - the place is like me: older and a bit run down. This truly is a case of getting what you pay for. I have two versions for you here. First one … I stayed in a room without a view. Also, I could hear everyone in the rooms around me - could hear when then talked, coughed, showered, flushed, walked, had the TV on, threw up, etc. EVERYTHING. I even passed gas once and the people in the next room laughed. Coincidence? I don't think so. The room and bath were really small. The place is run down but not dirty – no bad smells (beyond what I caused). Very friendly staff (and I’m not one to normally give out compliments). Thing is, for all the stuff that most snooty people would consider ‘unfit’, I was fine with. If you’re there to just spend time in your room, why did you come in the first place? I was normally to bed by 10 PM and up around 5:30 AM. Most everyone around me, according to shower noises, were up and running by 6:30 AM.Second version: My daughter stayed a couple of doors down from me and said she couldn’t hear any of what I mentioned hearing – said she couldn’t hear anyone in any of the rooms around her. Go figure. Also, she loved the view her room had of Grant Ave. And her room seemed a bit larger and nicer though I paid exactly the same price for it as the one I had.Final assessment: I’m 50 and would go there again. My daughter, 25, said she would also stay there again. I could easily have afforded much better but wanted something centrally located because I wanted to walk around SF, not drive. I did rent a car for 2 days to visit some sites further out (garage parking is on Sutter just 2 blocks from the Grant Plaza and cost $8 a night).	
Jan 29 2007	Stayed there several times	This is an old family-run hotel that serves its purpose, as far as I'm concerned: giving you an affordable place to crash in a decent location. I stay there when attending computer conventions down at the Moscone Center, and most other hotels in the area cost twice as much, which can really add up over the week.The rooms are spartan and a little cramped (though I have seen worse in S.F.) and the tiny shower stalls have low shower heads which can pose a problem for someone 6'2&quot;. That said, some other hotels in the same price range have you sharing a bathroom dorm-style. One peculiarity is that you must take the single elevator to get to your room, though you can leave by the stairs. (The problem is that the stairwell cannot be seen from the front desk, so they have to lock it from outside visitors.) I have never had anything stolen or damaged at the G.P., even though one time the maids moved my stuff to another room after some trouble with the card key reader. The staff seem courteous enough.There are some computers set up in the lobby for Internet, but it costs more than it's worth. (They also charge for local calls, but that seems to be a common practice in California.) I usually wander down to the Apple Store and grab a computer to check my webmail or use their free WI-FI. There's also a Starbucks a block away.The G.P. is actually inside Chinatown, so you can get some street noise, though I always seem to sleep like a log there regardless. It's a good place to dine without breaking the bank, and the souvenir-hunting is choice. (You'll pay a fraction of what you would at a tourist trap.)	
