Feb 11 2006	Not your Four Seasons but....	OK, I feel that the Grant Plaza definitely does not deserve the negative reviews it has garnered on this site. Sure, you're not going to get pampered like you would at the Four Seasons (which is like ~400 bucks a night) but for a budget traveler like me, this was perfect. It's got everything you would want: central location: close to Powell St Stn (about a 10 minute walk), in Chinatown. Not to mention clean beds, clean bathrooms, and a TV. I also arrived at the hotel at around 10 in the morning and even though check-in time was at 2pm, they let me go up to my room (although it hadn't been cleaned yet). Of course, I've stayed in better hotels, but this is SF, and to get a room downtown for 70 a night is a steal. I would definitely recommend this to the budget-conscious traveler who won't spend that much time in their hotel room anyway and only need a place to sleep and shower.	
Jan 20 2006	don't believe the photos! A dump	We found this hotel through the Lonely Planet guide. We're basically budget travellers and don't need much pampering or amenities. We just want a clean, decent place to relax and sleep. When we arrived, we were standing in a strangely neon lit lobby, a bit shabby, no big deal, but not as nice as the photos. The real kicker was when we stepped into our room. There were mystery stains on the walls(looked like old brown blood stains!). The sheets were very rumpled and smelled like perfume. It seemed obvious to us that no one actually changed the sheets after the last people left. We went down and asked for sheets and made the bed ourselves. THe bathroom was grimy and very run down. There were some hairs lying around and dirty grout. The furniture and the TV were VERY old and run down. The creepy thing is that there was a piece of TP stuffed into the eye piece in the door. It was very stuffy at night, and we ended up with coughing fits. I think we just weren't used to China Town air quality b/c we coughed more when we opened the windows. That was in the middle of the night. We were miserable and joked about the false advertising of the room photos that they have posted at the front of the hotel. You can see the same ones on this website. On the positive, I do like China Town and staff didn't try to charge us when we said we couldn't stay another night in this dump (we didn't say that exactly, but we thought it!). We ended up going to a place we had been to before, the Marina Inn. It's hard to believe the positive reviews. THey must have gotten the website photo room.	
