Oct 31 2005 	Would give 5-stars but . . .	Just got done with a 4-day/3-night stay in SF @ Grant Plaza. My review would be 5 &quot;stars&quot;/excellent, however, let's face it this is not a 5 star hotel. It is, however, a FANTASIC bargain. Consider that it meets the basic requirements I need in a hotel: a clean room, good shower, safe inside &amp; out, and a helpful staff. This cannot be said of all SF hotels. Yes the Grant doesn't have huge rooms/lobby, lavish appointments, indoor pool, etc or even a bathtub in every room. BUT, if you're looking for good, clean basic accomodations central to SF in general (and very close to Union Square, Chinatown and the Financial District) without paying the HUNDREDS of dollars most hotels in this area will cost you, this is certainly a place to consider and/or book. If you're looking for a place to spend your honeymoon (as another reviewer was) and want lavish surroundings - stay at the Ritz-Carlton - it's just a block away and will only cost you about 6 times as much/night (over $350/night MORE!) (based on on average price on this website on the day I posted this review). The savings is even greater when you factor in SF's ~15% hotel tax! My total cost @ the Grant Plaza was around $235, I estimate had I stayed at the Ritz I'd be talking about an almost $1,400+ bill. Sure, they're not the same, but I basically slept, showered and watched maybe an hour of TV at my hotel room during the 4 days I was there. The rest of the time I was either in seminars (the reason for the trip) and/or doing other SF things (shopping, eating &amp; seeing the sights). I will definitely consider booking at the Grant Plaza hotel for any (all?) my future trips to SF.	
Oct 17 2005	You Get What You Pay For	I had read a number of decent reviews of the Grant Plaza Hotel, some in guidebooks, and had booked a reservation based on these positive recommendations. I wish somebody had given posted the hard facts about this hotel. Here they are:1. This is indeed an inexpensive hotel and it is located in Chinatown.2. There's a reason why it is so inexpensive: it is aging not so gracefully, it isn't very clean (there was hair in both our sink and shower) and it really needs some work. We didn’t expect to be in the lap of luxury, but this hotel struck us as just a step or two above seedy.3. The rooms are not air conditioned. Which might not seem like a big deal, but (a) the streets around the hotel are very, very busy, (b) the windows in our room had broken locks and therefore could not be secured and (c) there was a fire escape of sorts outside of our window. We didn’t feel safe.The good news is that there seem to be very nice people running it. After we had checked in, we went to our room and very, very quickly decided we didn't want to stay there. We found another hotel (and paid more for a higher quality hotel) and let the front desk at the Grant Plaza Hotel know we didn't want to stay. No problem, we weren't charged a penny, and we left.	
